raw_output:
The issue that matters most is **whether the statute runs afoul of the Constitution’s (dormant) Commerce Clause and is therefore pre‑empted under the Supremacy Clause**.  In other words, the court will look at the extent to which the law:

* **Discriminates on its face against out‑of‑state interests** (e.g., requiring insurance only from in‑state carriers, giving hiring preference to state citizens, barring non‑resident aliens, and mandating a building material that exists only in the state);
* **Places a protectionist burden on interstate commerce** that is not justified by a legitimate local purpose;
* **Fails the Pike balancing test** (i.e., the burden on interstate commerce is clearly excessive in relation to the putative local benefits of “responsible insurance,” “higher standard of living,” “lower costs,” and “uniform aesthetics”).

If the statute is found to be protectionist or to unduly burden interstate commerce, it will be deemed unconstitutional under the Supremacy Clause because it is invalidated by the federal Constitution’s Commerce Clause.

The affidavit does **not** have to set forth the **particular words or exact content the agent expects to hear**.  

Under Title III (18 U.S.C. §§ 2511‑2512), the affidavit must allege:

* the identity of the person(s) whose communications are to be intercepted;  
* the particular facilities and method of interception;  
* the nature and seriousness of the criminal activity and the probable‑cause facts showing the communications will contain evidence of that crime;  
* the period of time for which interception is sought; and  
* that alternative investigative methods have been tried (or why they cannot be).  

But it is **not required** to specify the exact phrases, sentences, or “words” the government hopes to capture. The court need only be shown that probable cause exists that the communications, in general, will contain evidence of a crime.
